resort to Rome, of the wiser sort not for the holinesse
of the places, but for the frequence of godly &amp; learned
men then liuing in those places. Otherwise for
the holynesse of the place, S. Hierom ad Paulinum,
whether M. Sapleton sendeth vs, doth sufficiently declare

what was to be esteemed of it. 
                     Non Hierosolymis
fuisse, sed Hierosolymis bene vixisse laudandum est. It is
no praise to haue beene at Hierusalem, but to haue
liued well at Hierusalem. And speaking euen of our
owne countrye, he addeth. 
                     Et de Hierosolymis &amp; de Britannia
aequaliter patet aula coelestis. The court of heauen
is open equally, from Ierusalem and from Britain. Againe:
Beatus Hilarion cùm Palestinus esset &amp; in Palestina
