yet the fault is great when the tradition of the Apostles
is wilfully reiected. Whether it be like they deliuered any
needlesse or vnprofitable ceremonie, let wise men
iudge. After this, followeth a long and foolish dialogisme,
about the interpretation of Cyprians wordes.
What so euer the ministers of the sacraments be, what so euer
the handes are that dippe those that come to baptisme, what so
euer the brest is, out of which the holy wordes proceede, the authoritie
of operation giueth effect to all sacraments in the figure
of the crosse, and the name which is aboue all names, being
called vpon, by dispensers of the sacraments doth all. Martial
so scanneth these wordes, as though M. Calfhil
knewe not the difference betweene the power of
God, and the ministerie of man in the sacraments, whiche
Cyprian doth plainly distinguish in these wordes.
But to the purpose, Cyprian seemeth to make the figure
of the crosse a meane by which God worketh in
the sacraments. But in deede hee meaneth, that all sacraments
take their effect of the passion of Christ, as a
bare signe and token whereof they vsed the figure of
the crosse, and not as a meane whereby God worketh,
seeing it is confessed by Martial, that the sacraments if
the signe of the crosse be omitted lacke not their vertue. An other
foolish brable and vsherlike construing, he maketh
of Cyprians words, de baptismo Verborum solemnitas
&amp; sacri inuocatio nominis, &amp; signa attributa institutionibus
